05355nam a22008295i 9789048541041DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485410417 a10.1515/97890485410412doi  a(DE-B1597)617783  a(OCoLC)1302009689  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aBIO0060002bisacsh04a133.40942231 aValente, Michaela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJohann Wier :bDebating the Devil and Witches in Early Modern Europe /cMichaela Valente. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRenaissance History, Art and Culture ;v700tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- t1. History and historiography -- t2. Wier’s early years and apprenticeship (1515–1557) -- t3. Inside the labyrinth of spells -- t4. Between magic and science -- t5. Vince te ipsum -- t6. Demons, sorcerers, and witches -- t7. Scepticism and toleration -- t8. Reading and refuting Wier -- tConclusion -- tBibliography (primary sources) -- tBibliography (secondary sources) -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book deals with a fascinating and original claim in 16th-century Europe. Witches should be cured, not executed. It was the physician and scholar Johann Wier (1515-1588) who challenged the dominant idea. For his defense of witches, more than three centuries later, Sigmund Freud chose to put Wier’s work among the ten books to be read. According to Wier, Satan seduced witches, thus they did not deserve to be executed, but they must be cured for their melancholy. When the witch hunt was rising, Wier was the first to use some of the arguments adopted in the emerging debate on religious tolerance in defence of witches. This is the first overall study of Wier which offers an innovative view of his thought by highlighting Wier’s sources and his attempts to involve theologians, physicians, and philosophers in his fight against cruel witch hunts. Johann Wier: Debating the Devil and Witches situates and explains his claim as a result of a moral and religious path as well as the outcome of his medical experience. The book aims to provide an insightful examination of Wier’s works to read his pleas emphasizing the duty of every good Christian to not abandon anyone who strays from the flock of Christ. For these reasons, Wier was overwhelmed by bitter confutations, such as those of Jean Bodin, but he was also celebrated for his outstanding and prolific heritage for debating religious tolerance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDemonologyxHistoryy16th centuryzEurope. 0aMedicinexHistoryy16th centuryzEurope. 0aWitchcraftxHistoryy16th centuryzEurope. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aHistory. 4aReligion and Theology. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh  aWitches, Devil, Wier.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076709408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2022 Part 2z978311076700108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2022 Englishz978311099296008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2022z9783110992939oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048541041?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048541041423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/co